---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { DICTIONARY_URL } from '../lib/site';
import skillRaw from '../../skill/SKILL.md?raw';
---

<Base title="Skill">
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Install the skill</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300">
      The skill makes your coding agent fetch the dictionary <em>before</em> it builds,
      and follow it for the rest of the task. It's one markdown file.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-lg font-semibold">1. Save this as <code>SKILL.md</code></h2>
    <pre
      class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg bg-zinc-100 p-4 text-sm dark:bg-zinc-900"><code>{skillRaw}</code></pre>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-lg font-semibold">2. Put it where your agent looks</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300">For Claude Code:</p>
    <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300">
      <li>
        Personal (all projects):
        <code>~/.claude/skills/agents-dictionary/SKILL.md</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Project (this repo only):
        <code>.claude/skills/agents-dictionary/SKILL.md</code>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300">
      Other agents: drop the same file into your agent's skills/instructions
      directory, or paste the body into your <code>AGENTS.md</code>.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-lg font-semibold">No skill? Just paste the URL</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300">
      You can skip the skill entirely and tell your agent at the start of a build:
    </p>
    <pre
      class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg bg-zinc-100 p-4 text-sm dark:bg-zinc-900"><code>Read {DICTIONARY_URL} and follow it for this build.</code></pre>
  </section>
</Base>
